logistic_regression_example

Dan Ladd

In this supervised machine learning application, I use logistic regression to assess if an employee is at risk of leaving an organization based on attributes and characteristics of their employment.

After loading the data and performing basic cleaning, I discover that the sample needs to be balanced so classes are roughly equal for the target feature. Given logistic regression can be sensitive to small sample sizes, I rebalance my sample using an oversampling technique. I then review descriptive statistics and plot visuals for both numerical and categorical features. After gaining a baseline, I look at feature correlation and decide to reduce dimensions to avoid potential mulicollinearity issues.

I then begin the machine learning process. After partitioning and training my logistic regression model, I evaluate its perfromance against the validation data set. I utalize a confusion matrix and AUC-ROC plot to understand and visualize the models perfromance.

Load and Preview data
In this project, I’m interested in learning about how different employee attributes and characteristics contribute to corporate attrition. I’ll use the at.risk feature as my target. A value of Yes is given for an employee who has left the company, and a value of No is given to retained employees. Statistics will help me understand if and how predictor features relate to the target.

A preview of the data shows me it has been read into R and organized as a data.frame. There are twelve features including the target feature. Some features are categorical and others numerical. There are both discrete and continuous features.

Missing Data
It’s a miracle. There is no missing data! Typically, cleaning missing data is the logical next step. Cleaning missing data can be performed using several different imputation stratigies. The preferred strategy is often based on domain knowledge. Excessive missing data may result in dimension reduction via removing features all together. Failure to handle missing data can easily lead to poor insights, forecasts, and model building.

Review target feature class balance It’s important to have a good balance of the target features classes when applying logistic regression to classification problems. After discovering the target imbalance, I use an oversampling technique to rebalance the data.

# review balance of target variables classes
table(employee_data$at.risk) / nrow(employee_data)
## 
##        No       Yes 
## 0.8387755 0.1612245
# rebalance target by oversampling "yes"
employee_data <- upSample(x = employee_data[, -which(names(employee_data) == "at.risk")], y = employee_data$at.risk)

# re institute feature name and check new balance
employee_data <- employee_data %>%
  rename(at.risk = Class)

table(employee_data$at.risk)
## 
##   No  Yes 
## 1233 1233

Descriptive Statistics of Numerical Features
Now that I’ve gained a basic understanding of the data and performed some preliminary preprocessing, I’m ready to take a closer look at each feature and gain a general impression.

In review of numerical feature central tendency and dispersion, I can see that there are probable outliers in all numerical features except age. Standard deviation also suggests that there is larger variability in the age, yrs.at.company, and monthly.income features. This is consistent with their larger ranges. Skew shows me that all features have a positive distribution with age having a normal distribution. yrs.since.promotion, yrs.at.company, and monthly.income have notably more positive skews suggesting that higher values in these features are less common and extend further to the right. High kurtosis supports this and suggests that the most influential outliers are within the yrs.since.promotion and yrs.at.company features. Standard error suggests acceptable fluctuations of the sample from the population across all numerical features.

Outlier Desicioning I have to decide how to handle the outliers. I review each outlier and decide weather it’s meaningful to our objective or not. A data entry typo would not be meaningful for example. Domain and project knowledge guide me in deciding weather or not to keep outliers. After scrutinizing each features outliers, I determine that they are all reasonable and relevant to the problem we’re drawing insights on. Ultimately, I keep all ourliers.

yrs.in.current.role outliers
Examining the boxplot shows me that I have at least two outliers in the yrs.in.current.role feature. To take a closer look, I calculate the IQR, lowerbound, and upper bound. I’m then able to identify and print a tibble of the observations with outliers in yrs.at.current.role. I can see that there are actually 6 outliers in this feature. All appear to be litigant and reasonable observations that will provide value to my model. I choose to keep outliers since they should have a positive effect on the accuracy of my model.

# boxplot of yrs.in.current.role
ggplot(employee_data, mapping = aes(yrs.in.current.role)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "blue") 

# Calculate Q1, Q3, and IQR
current_role_q1 <- quantile(employee_data$yrs.in.current.role, 0.25)
current_role_q3 <- quantile(employee_data$yrs.in.current.role, 0.75)
current_role_iqr <- current_role_q3 - current_role_q1

# Define the lower and upper bounds for outliers
current_role_lb <- current_role_q1 - 1.5 * current_role_iqr
current_role_ub <- current_role_q3 + 1.5 * current_role_iqr

# Extract outliers
current_role_outliers <- employee_data$yrs.in.current.role[employee_data$yrs.in.current.role < current_role_lb | employee_data$yrs.in.current.role > current_role_ub]

# Print outliers

Model to access categorical correlation
Next I fit a logistic regression model to my data and summarize the results. This helps me understand additional correlations in my categorical features. The deviance residuals express a good model fit considering deviations from actual to estimate. Statistically significant features with p-values of less than 0.05 include gender, age, job.level, yrs.since.promotion. yrs.with.manager, yrs.with.manager, monthly .income, and job.travel. These features have the greatest impact on the outcome of the target.Reviewing the generalized VIF (GVIF), I see that multicollinearity is likely an issue with the yrs.with.manager feature. GVIF is equal to more than 2 indicating multicollinearity. Additionally, GVIF shows me that monthly.income may also pose multicollinearity issues. Given what I’ve learned up to now, monthly.income multicollinearity is probably linked to several other features.

In brief summary, I find that as age increases, employees become less at risk of leaving. An employees education level has less of an effect on their attrition than other factors. Job level is connected to attrition, especially at the highest level, senior leadership. More yrs without a promotion increases the risk of an employee leaving. More yrs under the same manager, and a higher monthly income lesson the chance of an employee leaving. lastly, more job travel requirements lead to increased chances of an employee leaving.

logit_model <- glm(at.risk ~ gender + age + education + job.level + performance.rating + yrs.since.promotion + yrs.at.company + yrs.in.current.role + yrs.with.manager + monthly.income + job.travel.requirments, data = employee_data, family = binomial)

The Logistic Regression model appears to have sub par accuracy. It can make an accurate prediction on weather or not an employee is at risk of leaving the company about 65% of the time. Although this may seem low, context is detrimental to the usefulness and deployment of data science. We wouldn’t accept this model if it was built for the purpose of recommending the administration of a pharmaceutical. However, in our context of employee attrition, the model provides some value. The model could be used to help HR departments combat employee turnover with some accuracy. It would help HR departments strategically focus on employees that are statistically more likely to turnover. Wrongful classification in this context has no negative impact on the subject so we can accept that th model may be wrong about 35% of the time. The model provides strategic guidance to the HR Department which should result in better overall employee retention. Additionally, it could be deployed temporarily while other models that consider non linear relationships, like random forest, are built and tested.

Begin Machine Learning process

Now that I have a strong understanding of my data, I prepare it for logistic regression machine learning, I start by partitioning the data into training and validation sets. I then create a task and a learner for the training partition. I then train the model on the training data.

# set seed to ensure reproducibility in future
set.seed(112)

# partition data into 80% training purposes and 20% validation purposes.
train_index <- sample(row.names(employee_data), 0.80*dim(employee_data)[1])
valid_index <- setdiff(row.names(employee_data), train_index)

train_ar <- employee_data[train_index,]
valid_ar <- employee_data[valid_index,]
# create a classification task indicting at.risk as the target. 
at_risk_logit_task <- TaskClassif$new(id = "logit_task", backend = train_ar, target = "at.risk")
# create a learner specifying logistic regression
at_risk_logit_learner <- lrn("classif.log_reg", predict_type = "prob")
# train the model on the training partition
ar_logit <- at_risk_logit_learner$train(at_risk_logit_task)

Review Model Performance
Quantify Performance with Confusion Matrix
Next I create a task for my validation dataset and make predictions. I review performance by generating a confusion matrix. The confusion matrix shows that overall accuracy is about 64%. It performs better at identifying positive cases Yes, at 68.11%, than it does at negative, No, cases at 59.58%. False negatives, where Yes cases are incorrectly predicted as No are the least reliable piece of the model. Overall, the model’s predictions are moderately reliable. Given the previous logit model I used to access correlation, these results are as expected. Although the model is not highly accurate, it provides value in the context in which it is being applied. The model is an improvement over random chance especially when considering that it performs better at predicting Yes cases than No cases which is more detrimental to it’s application.

# create a classification task for the validation data
valid_task <- TaskClassif$new(id = "valid_task", backend = valid_ar, target = "at.risk")

# Predict on the validation dataset
pred <- at_risk_logit_learner$predict(valid_task)
# Get predicted classes
predicted_classes <- pred$response
true_classes <- valid_ar$at.risk

# Create a confusion matrix

confusionMatrix(as.factor(predicted_classes), as.factor(true_classes))

Closing Statement

In conclusion, deployment of this machine learning application could provide some strategic guidance to HR. However, it leaves a lot of room for improvement. The existing model could be made slightly better through hyperparameter tuning but that would not drastically improve the models performance in it’s current sub-par state. Additionally, the existing model could be improved by normalizing or standardizing some of the features with large ranges like monthly.income. Those features may be overly contributing to results given that logistic regressions gradient-based optimization makes it susceptible to large differences in feature scales. New feature data could also be introduced to help improve model performance.

Additionally, other types of algorithms could be applied to the data to inprove performance. I would recommend first normalizing the age, and monthly.income features If accuracy was still shy of expectations, I would recommend applying Random Forest as a next step. Random Forest is a decision tree ensemble approach that is resistant to differences in feature scale. More importantly, Random Forest considers non linear relationships between predictor and target features.
